I can&#39;t really understand your overall goal or logic.

But, if you want two pieces of code to run independently, you use threads. From C++11, you can do it in a standard way, with std::thread. I changed your code to make it run in threads (without understanding the goal). I used lambdas.

 
    #include &lt;thread&gt;
	#include &lt;iostream&gt;

    int main() {
    
        int True = 1;
        int UnchangebleValue = 1;
    
        int DoThis = 1;
        int DoThat = 1;

        std::thread t1([&amp;DoThis, &amp;DoThat, &amp;UnchangebleValue, True]() {
			while (DoThis &gt;= True || DoThat &lt;= True) {
				if (DoThis &gt;= True) {
					DoThis += UnchangebleValue;
					std::cout &lt;&lt; DoThis &lt;&lt; std::endl;
					std::this_thread::sleep_for(std::chrono::milliseconds(1000));
				}}
			});

		std::thread t2([&amp;DoThis, &amp;DoThat, &amp;UnchangebleValue, True]() {
			if (DoThat &lt;= True) {
				DoThat -= UnchangebleValue;
				std::cout &lt;&lt; DoThat &lt;&lt; std::endl;
			}});

		t1.join();
		t2.join();
    
        return 0;
    }

Note that there is no synchronization in the code above. In a real project, you&#39;d want atomic&lt;int&gt; values, and/or mutexes (mutices).

